I created this thread as a place on this site where anyone can share information on Vietnam or the military that they came across and feel would be interesting to share with others.<br><br>
On that note, I recently read something I though might be interesting to post.<br><br>
The source of this is the Washington Times and it was printed in the June/July 1997 VFW Magazine.  Here it is word for word, exactly as it was printed:<br><br>
Army Too &quot;Manly&quot;, Claims Advisor<br>
Madeline Morris, a consultant to the Secretary of the Army, would exorcise the Army of &quot;masculine&quot; tendencies with the aim of becoming &quot;ungendered.&quot;  So-called &quot;macho posturing&quot; should be replaced by the cohesiveness demonstrated by &quot;Communist Party cells,&quot; she says.<br>
     The Duke University law professor offered these enlightened views in her article, &quot;By Force of Arms: Rape, War and Military Culture,&quot; published in Duke Law Review Journal:  &quot;There is substantial evidence. . . of themes of hypermasculinity, adversarial sexual beliefs, promiscuity, hostility toward women and possibly acceptance of violence against women within current military culture.&quot;<br>
     Among Morris' impeccable credentials: she served as a consultant to the legal Department of Playboy Enterprises (Playboy Magazine). <br><br>

